WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.885
The periodic table is not a colourful poster designed to
frighten classrooms. It is a map - every element type
nature can build with, laid out in order.

2
00:00:10.885 --> 00:00:17.141
Each tile means: here is one kind of atom. One tile, one
element, no repeats.

3
00:00:17.141 --> 00:00:26.974
Hydrogen is H. Oxygen is O. Carbon is C. Copper is Cu.
Iron is Fe. Gold is Au.

4
00:00:26.974 --> 00:00:34.472
Some symbols are obvious. C for carbon is friendly. O for
oxygen is practically waving.

5
00:00:34.472 --> 00:00:51.116
Others are old-name surprises. Iron is Fe, from the Latin
ferrum. Copper is Cu, from cuprum. Gold is Au, from aurum.
Chemistry keeps its history tucked inside the labels.

6
00:00:51.116 --> 00:00:56.955
You do not need to memorise the whole table today. You
need to know how to read it.

7
00:00:56.955 --> 00:01:06.555
Every element has an address on the map: its atomic
number. The tiles are arranged by that number - in order,
no gaps.

8
00:01:06.555 --> 00:01:15.965
Hydrogen is number one. Helium is two. Carbon is six.
Oxygen is eight. Copper is twenty-nine. Gold is
seventy-nine.

9
00:01:15.965 --> 00:01:23.862
The neighbourhoods have patterns too. Metals fill the left
and middle of the map. Non-metals cluster toward the
right.

10
00:01:23.862 --> 00:01:36.595
Columns are called groups - elements in the same group
often behave in related ways, like family members. Rows
are called periods - they show the order running across

11
00:01:36.595 --> 00:01:47.754
So one tile hands you three things: the symbol, the name,
and the address number. It is not asking you to panic. It
is giving you coordinates.

12
00:01:47.754 --> 00:02:02.173
When the control room lights up C, think carbon: pencil
graphite, diamond, and nearly everything alive. When it
lights up O, think oxygen: air, water, and a very long

13
00:02:02.173 --> 00:02:14.212
Fe means iron: nails, tools, and rust waiting to happen.
Cu means copper: wires, coins, and that warm orange-brown
shine.

14
00:02:14.212 --> 00:02:32.803
Here is where the labels earn their keep. In a particle
diagram, a carbon atom and an oxygen atom might both be
drawn as plain circles. The letters C and O tell you they

15
00:02:32.803 --> 00:02:40.077
The periodic table is the key to that code. Different
symbol, different atomic number, different element.
Always.

16
00:02:40.077 --> 00:02:52.002
One tile you will never find: water. Water is not an
element. It is built from hydrogen and oxygen. The table
lists the building blocks, not everything built from them.

17
00:02:52.002 --> 00:03:07.212
Run the same test on salt. Na is sodium, Cl is chlorine -
both on the table. Sodium chloride, table salt, is not a
new tile. It is a compound made from two tiles you already

18
00:03:07.212 --> 00:03:16.983
We are saving electron shells for later. Today's big idea
is enough: the periodic table is a map, not a memory
punishment.

19
00:03:16.983 --> 00:03:28.645
So when you spot Cu on a copper wire or Fe on a lab card,
think: atom type, with an address. When you see the whole
table, think: the map of everything matter is made from.
